DESCRIPTION:
Azurite is a very intense blue rather soft stone. its the blue cousin to malachite and rarely comes cut and faceted.

LORE:said to brake down illusions and to enhance communication it also a guidance to psychic self and help in understanding fears and desires.
Artists say it aid in creativity since it illuminate the mind and gives strong visionary power
scribers and magic users tend to use a powerdy form of this stone since it last longer then most inc.

DESCRIPTION:
Peridot's subtle and scintillating green tones range from pale yellowish green into a pleasant olive green. Also known as the "evening emerald" since its green appears to be more intense in reduced light. Because of the way peridot splits and bends the rays of light passing through it, it has a velvety, "sleepy" appearance - a shining rich glow, and a slightly greasy luster. 
LORE:
it is belived to removes stress, fear, guilt, activates personal growth and by some it have the power to even show hidden ways and concealed doors

A transparent gem in colors of red, brown-green, or violet. This is the red variety.

Garnets come in many colors but, as of the Year of Wild Magic, 1372 DR, the violet hue was the most valuable and called rhodolite[ while the other varieties and fallen out of favor and were valued in the fancy stone price range.

In some faiths and folklore, garnets are considered the solidified blood of the divine avatars.[4] To the uninitiated, garnets has the reputation of being worthless for magical use.

Garnet is a common stone among the drow, a gem worn by drow of average station. There was a distinction regarding color preference depending on the profession of the wearer. Deep red is favored by warriors, while the priestesses of Lolth favored violet ones.

DESCRIPTION:
This stone comes in various shades of blue, green and is often shaped and worked on since it rather soft and rarely ever shatter
LORE:
Horsemen with often place a sliver of this stone in a horse's harness as a sign of good luck.

DESCRIPTION:
Waterstar is also called achroite or colourless tourmaline. The stone is riddled with flaws and inclusions and hence only a small portion is fit for cutting
LORE:
rumors is that if danger is upcoming this stone turns opaque and becomes heavy to carry. A bard and witness claim to have seen one shatter to bits just seconds before the owner was killed by a arrow
The brew within is murky and undoubtedly packs a punch.

LORE SUCCESS!!! This is the old Mooting Hall and residence of the the MacKorart clan. An ancient clan, they have distant ancestral ties to the MacRyker and as a result the MacPontys, and were among the first of the clans to migrate west to the Clyft when King Rhydian Kendrick founded the Kingdom of Corwell and centred its capital in the west of Gwynneth
